const a = [
  {"id":385,"text":"Which of the following key enzymes is required for the synthesis of acetylcholine?","explanation":null,"reference":"Snell RS. Clinical Neuroanatomy. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer Health/Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2010: 273.","responses":[{"text":"Choline acetyltransferase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Choline acetylsynthetase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Choline synthetase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Choline acyltransferase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetyl cholineaminase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16104,"text":"Which of the following veins is not a tributary of the cavernous sinus?","explanation":"The vein that is not a tributary of the cavernous sinus among the options given is the **straight sinus**. The cavernous sinus, a large collection of thin-walled veins located on either side of the pituitary gland, receives blood from several veins, including the superior and inferior ophthalmic veins, the sphenoparietal sinus, and sometimes the central vein of the retina. However, the straight sinus is a dural venous sinus located within the brain, which primarily drains blood from the deep midline structures of the brain and cerebrospinal fluid from the ventricular system. It does not directly contribute to the cavernous sinus but instead connects to the confluence of sinuses at the back of the head, where several dural sinuses meet.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 424.","responses":[{"text":"Straight sinus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior ophthalmic vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Central vein of retina","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior ophthalmic vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sphenoparietal sinus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16105,"text":"Which of the following veins drains into the superior sagittal sinus?","explanation":"The veins that drain into the superior sagittal sinus are the **superior cerebral veins**. The superior sagittal sinus is a dural venous sinus running along the top of the skull in the midline. The superior cerebral veins, which drain the superficial aspects of the cerebral hemispheres, typically traverse the subarachnoid space and empty into the superior sagittal sinus. They carry blood from the upper surfaces of the brain and are essential for venous drainage from these areas.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, the deep middle cerebral veins and striate veins are involved in draining the deeper structures of the brain and do not directly drain into the superior sagittal sinus. The superficial middle cerebral veins typically drain into the cavernous or sphenoparietal sinuses. The anterior cerebral veins, associated with the anterior parts of the cerebral hemispheres, also do not directly drain into the superior sagittal sinus.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 423.","responses":[{"text":"Deep middle cerebral veins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superficial middle cerebral veins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Striate veins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior cerebral veins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior cerebral veins","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16106,"text":"Which of the following cranial nerves does not originate at the pontomedullary junction of the brainstem?","explanation":"The **olfactory nerve** (cranial nerve I) does not originate at the pontomedullary junction of the brainstem. The olfactory nerve is responsible for the sense of smell and originates in the olfactory epithelium in the upper part of the nasal cavity. Its fibers then pass through the cribriform plate of the ethmoid bone to reach the olfactory bulb, located beneath the frontal lobe of the brain. \r\n\r\nThe facial nerve (vranial Nerve vII), vestibulocochlear nerve (cranial nerve VIII), abducens nerve (cranial nerve VI), and nervus intermedius (a part of the facial nerve complex) all originate at or near the pontomedullary junction. The facial nerve and nervus intermedius emerge at the cerebellopontine angle, while the vestibulocochlear nerve also emerges in this region. The abducens nerve originates from the pons, close to the pontomedullary junction.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 326, 327.","responses":[{"text":"Olfactory nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Facial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vestibulocochlear nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abducens nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nervus intermedius","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16107,"text":"Which of the following arteries is not a part of the circle of Willis?","explanation":"The artery that is not a part of the circle of Willis is the **middle cerebral artery**. The **circle of Willis** is a ring-like arterial structure located at the base of the brain, providing a collateral circulation pathway. It comprises the anterior cerebral arteries (connected by the anterior communicating artery), the posterior cerebral arteries (connected to the internal carotid arteries by the posterior communicating arteries), and the internal carotid arteries themselves. The middle cerebral artery, while an important vessel supplying a significant portion of the brain's lateral surface, is not a component of the circle of Willis. It branches off from the internal carotid artery but lies outside the ring formed by the circle of Willis.","reference":"(1) Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 468.\r\n\r\n(2) Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 891.","responses":[{"text":"Middle cerebral artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior cerebral artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior cerebral artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior communicating artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior communicating artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16108,"text":"Which of the following statements regarding the long association fibers is incorrect?","explanation":"Long association fibers in the brain are bundles of axons that connect distant regions of the cerebral cortex within the same hemisphere. **They are not primarily involved in connecting adjacent gyri, which is the function of short association fibers, also known as U-fibers.** Long association fibers, such as the cingulum and the superior longitudinal fasciculus, indeed connect different lobes or distant cortical areas. The cingulum wraps around the corpus callosum linking the frontal, parietal, and temporal lobes, while the superior longitudinal fasciculus connects the frontal lobe to the occipital and temporal lobes. These fibers are composed of white matter and lie deep beneath the cerebral cortex.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 264.","responses":[{"text":"Lie deep beneath the cerebral cortex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior longitudinal fasciculus is the largest bundle of nerve fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They connect adjacent gyri","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The cingulum is an example of long association fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Composed of white matter","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16109,"text":"A 44-year-old patient presents to the outpatient clinic with the complaint of being unable to recall any recently occurring events. Which of the following brain structures is responsible for converting short-term memory into long-term memory?","explanation":"The brain structure responsible for converting short-term memory into long-term memory is the **hippocampus**. The hippocampus, a part of the limbic system, plays a critical role in memory processing, particularly in the consolidation of information from short-term to long-term memory. It is involved in the formation of new memories and is crucial for learning and recalling spatial relationships and declarative memories (memories of facts and events). Other listed structures like the parahippocampal gyrus, fornix, prefrontal cortex, and indusium griseum are involved in various aspects of memory and cognition, but the hippocampus is specifically key for the conversion of short-term to long-term memories. Damage or dysfunction in the hippocampus is often associated with difficulties in forming new long-term memories, as seen in conditions like Alzheimer's disease and amnesia.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 739.","responses":[{"text":"Indusium griseum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fornix","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hippocampus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Parahippocampal gyrus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prefrontal cortex","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16110,"text":"A 67-year-old male patient admitted to the neurology ward is observed to have intention tremor and cerebellar ataxia. Radiological scans reveal a pontine infarct. Which of the following fibers is most likely damaged in this case?","explanation":"The **corticopontocerebellar tract** is involved in the coordination of movement. It carries information from the cerebral cortex to the pontine nuclei, which then relay this information to the cerebellum via the middle cerebellar peduncles. Damage to these fibers in the pontine region can lead to deficits in motor coordination, manifesting as cerebellar ataxia and intention tremor (tremor that occurs during voluntary movements). The other options, such as sympathetic and parasympathetic fibers, are related to autonomic functions, and the corticospinal tract is primarily associated with voluntary motor control. Auditory fibers are not typically implicated in the presentation of motor coordination issues.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 217, 241.","responses":[{"text":"Corticopontocerebellar tract","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Parasympathetic fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Auditory fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sympathetic fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Corticospinal tract","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16111,"text":"Which of the following is not a feature of postganglionic neurons of the sympathetic nervous system?","explanation":"In reality, postganglionic sympathetic fibers are typically **long**. This is because the cell bodies of these neurons are located in autonomic ganglia, which are often quite distant from the effector organs they innervate. Therefore, the axons of these neurons need to be long to reach their target organs. These neurons do originate away from the effector organs, their cell bodies are located in peripheral autonomic ganglia, they are largely unmyelinated, and they are predominantly noradrenergic (meaning they release norepinephrine as a neurotransmitter).","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 388, 391.","responses":[{"text":"Are short in length","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The cell bodies of postganglionic neurons are in autonomic ganglia located peripherally","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Originate away from the effector organs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Noradrenergic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Unmyelinated","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16112,"text":"A 62-year-old male patient is diagnosed with early-stage Parkinson's disease. The neurological examination reveals a slight resting tremor of the left hand, slow gait, and lack of the normal range of facial expression. Which of the following is the most likely site of the degenerative changes at this stage of the patient's disease?","explanation":"In the case of early-stage Parkinson's disease with symptoms manifesting primarily on the left side of the body, as indicated by the left-hand tremor, the most likely site of degenerative changes is the **right substantia nigra**. Parkinson's disease is marked by the loss of dopaminergic neurons in the substantia nigra, a region in the midbrain that plays a crucial role in the control of movements. The brain's organization is such that each side (hemisphere) largely controls the opposite side of the body. Therefore, the degeneration of dopaminergic neurons in the right substantia nigra would lead to motor symptoms predominantly affecting the left side of the body. As the disease progresses, it typically becomes more bilateral, affecting both substantia nigrae, but initial symptoms often appear unilaterally.","reference":"(1) Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 317.\r\n\r\n(2) Ghoneim A, Pollard C, Tyagi A, Jampana R. Substantia nigra micro-haemorrhage causing ipsilateral unilateral Parkinsonism and abnormal dopamine transporter scan uptake. BJR | Case Reports. Published October 8, 2020. Accessed March 23, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7869125/","responses":[{"text":"Right substantia niagra","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Right globus pallidus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bilateral substantia niagra","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left globus pallidus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left substantia niagra","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16113,"text":"Which of the following structures forms the anterior boundary of the interventricular foramen of Monro?","explanation":"The structure that forms the anterior boundary of the interventricular foramen of Monro is the **anterior column of fornix**. The interventricular foramen, also known as the foramen of Monro, is a channel that connects the lateral ventricles of the brain with the third ventricle. The anterior column of the fornix is a key structure in this area; it curves down in front of the foramen of Monro. The fornix is a C-shaped bundle of nerve fibers that acts as a major output tract of the hippocampus and is involved in memory processing. The body of fornix forms its central part, the posterior columns lead towards the mammillary bodies, the crura are its posterior descending parts, and the fimbriae are fiber tracts close to the hippocampus. Among these, the anterior column specifically contributes to the anatomy surrounding the foramen of Monro.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 304.","responses":[{"text":"Crura of fornix","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior column of fornix","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Body of fornix","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior column of fornix","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fimbria of fornix","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16114,"text":"A 50-year-old male patient undergoes a CT scan which reveals a tumor of the midbrain. It shows symmetrical distension of the lateral ventricles and the third ventricle. Which of the following structures is most likely obstructed by the tumor in this case?","explanation":"The **cerebral aqueduct,** also known as the aqueduct of Sylvius, is a narrow channel in the midbrain that connects the third ventricle above with the fourth ventricle below. A tumor in the midbrain can compress or obstruct this aqueduct, leading to a buildup of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) in the ventricles above the blockage, namely the lateral and third ventricles, resulting in their enlargement. This condition is known as obstructive or non-communicating hydrocephalus. The foramina of Luschka and Magendie are openings from the fourth ventricle, and the central canal is a channel within the spinal cord, while the foramina of Monro connect the lateral ventricles to the third ventricle and are located higher in the brain's ventricular system.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 456.","responses":[{"text":"Central canal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cerebral aqueduct","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Foramen of Magendie","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Foramen of Monroe","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Foramen of Luschka","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16155,"text":"A 53-year-old patient was brought to the emergency department after a fall. MRI scan reveals a slipped disc at the L3 level. Neurological examination shows that the patient has a bilateral loss of pain, temperature, and light touch sensation below the level of the lesion, bilateral lower motor neuron paralysis in the segment of the lesion, and bilateral spastic paralysis below the level of the lesion. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis in this case?","explanation":"**Anterior cord syndrome** is characterized by damage to the anterior part of the spinal cord, which typically affects the motor function and pain and temperature sensation, while sparing proprioception and vibration sensation. The symptoms of bilateral loss of pain, temperature, and light touch sensation below the level of the lesion, combined with bilateral lower motor neuron paralysis at the level of the lesion and bilateral spastic paralysis below the level of the lesion, align with the typical presentation of anterior cord syndrome. This condition often results from compromised blood flow to the anterior spinal artery, which can be caused by conditions such as a herniated disc.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 168.","responses":[{"text":"Syringomyelia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior cord syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Brown-Séquard syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Central cord syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete cord transection syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16156,"text":"The sensation of discriminative touch, vibratory sense, and conscious muscle joint proprioception of the lower limbs passes from the posterior root ganglia to the postcentral gyrus through which of the following pathways?","explanation":"The **fasciculus gracilis,** part of the dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway, carries these specific sensory modalities from the lower limbs and lower part of the body. Once these nerve fibers reach the medulla oblongata, they synapse and then decussate (cross to the opposite side) as internal arcuate fibers, forming the **medial lemniscus.** The medial lemniscus then continues to ascend through the brainstem to the thalamus, which relays the sensory information to the postcentral gyrus of the cerebral cortex for processing. The lateral spinothalamic pathway, in contrast, carries pain and temperature sensations, and the anterior spinothalamic tract conveys light touch and pressure sensations.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 143.","responses":[{"text":"Lateral spinothalamic and spinal lemniscus pathway","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior spinothalamic and spinal lemniscus pathway","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fasciculus gracilis and spinal lemniscus pathway","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral spinothalamic and medial lemniscus pathway","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fasciculus gracilis and medial lemniscus pathway","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16159,"text":"Which of the following embryological structures gives rise to the dorsal sensory horn of the spinal cord?","explanation":"The embryological structure that gives rise to the dorsal sensory horn of the spinal cord is the **alar plate**. During the development of the spinal cord, the neural tube differentiates into distinct regions. The alar plate is located dorsally and is responsible for the development of the sensory areas of the spinal cord, including the dorsal horn, which processes sensory information. In contrast, the basal plate, located ventrally, gives rise to the motor neurons of the ventral horn. The marginal layer becomes the white matter of the spinal cord, containing the myelinated axons. The roof plate and floor plate are specialized regions that serve as signaling centers for the patterning of the neural tube but do not directly form the dorsal or ventral horns.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 315.","responses":[{"text":"Roof plate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alar plate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Floor plate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Marginal layer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basal plate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16164,"text":"A parasympathetic nerve arising from the brainstem influences the lungs. The cell body of this nerve lies in which of the following nuclei?","explanation":"The parasympathetic nerve that influences the lungs has its cell body in the **dorsal nucleus of vagus**. This nucleus is part of the vagus nerve (Cranial Nerve X), which provides the primary parasympathetic innervation to the lungs. The vagus nerve, arising from the medulla oblongata in the brainstem, carries out various functions including the regulation of internal organ functions such as heart rate, gastrointestinal motility, and, importantly, the constriction and relaxation of the smooth muscles in the lungs.\r\n\r\nThe Edinger-Westphal nucleus is involved in pupillary constriction and lens accommodation, the inferior and superior salivatory nuclei are involved in salivation, and the lacrimation nucleus (not lacrimatory nucleus) is involved in tear production. These nuclei, while also part of the parasympathetic system, do not innervate the lungs.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 343.","responses":[{"text":"Dorsal nucleus of vagus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior salivatory nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior salivatory nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lacrimatory nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Edinger-Westphal nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16165,"text":"A 24-year-old patient presents to the emergency department after a road accident with complaints of headache, nausea, vomiting \u0026 an altered level of consciousness. An X-ray of the skull reveals a fracture of the cribriform plate of the ethmoid bone. Which of the following cranial nerves passes through the foramina of this fractured bone?","explanation":"The cranial nerve that passes through the foramina of the cribriform plate of the ethmoid bone is **CN I**, the olfactory nerve. The olfactory nerve is responsible for the sense of smell. The axons of the olfactory receptor neurons, located in the nasal mucosa, pass through the tiny holes in the cribriform plate to reach the olfactory bulbs on the underside of the frontal lobe of the brain. A fracture of the cribriform plate can result in damage to these nerves, potentially leading to anosmia (loss of the sense of smell) and cerebrospinal fluid leakage.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 326, 327.","responses":[{"text":"CN IV","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CN V","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CN II","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CN III","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CN I","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16167,"text":"During a routine examination of a newborn baby in the pediatric clinic, the physician notices a depression of the anterior fontanelle (membranous gap in between bones of the skull). The depressed fontanelle lies between which of the following bones?","explanation":"The anterior fontanelle, the largest fontanelle in a newborn baby and often referred to as the \"soft spot,\" is located at the intersection of four skull bones: **the frontal bone and the two parietal bones.** Fontanelles are membranous gaps that are present at birth and gradually close as the child grows. The anterior fontanelle typically closes by 18-24 months of age. Its depression can be a sign of dehydration or other clinical conditions in infants and requires further evaluation.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 191.","responses":[{"text":"Parietal and temporal bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Parietal and petrous part of temporal bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Parietal and mastoid part of temporal bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Frontal and parietal bone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Parietal and occipital bone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16168,"text":"A patient who suffered from a road traffic accident is brought to the emergency room with a skull fracture involving bones of the anterior cranial fossa. Which of the following skull bones is most likely to be fractured in this case?","explanation":"The anterior cranial fossa comprises the frontal bone, the ethmoid bone (specifically, the cribriform plate), and the **lesser wings of the sphenoid bone.** Among these, the lesser wings of the sphenoid are more prone to fracture in trauma cases involving the anterior cranial fossa. This area is relatively fragile and susceptible to injury, especially in significant trauma such as a road traffic accident. The greater wings of the sphenoid, temporal bone, parietal bone, and clivus are components of the middle and posterior cranial fossae, and are less likely to be involved in fractures of the anterior cranial fossa.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 841.","responses":[{"text":"Clivius","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lesser wings of sphenoid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Parietal bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Greater wings of sphenoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Temporal bone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16176,"text":"A diabetic patient is observed to have mydriasis while undergoing an examination in an ophthalmology clinic. All other eye movements are normal. The nerve most likely affected in this case arises from which of the following brain stem nuclei?","explanation":"The **Edinger-Westphal nucleus** nucleus is the parasympathetic preganglionic nucleus of the oculomotor nerve (Cranial Nerve III) and is involved in pupillary constriction (miosis) and lens accommodation for near vision. Damage or dysfunction in the parasympathetic fibers arising from this nucleus, often due to diabetes-related neuropathy, can lead to mydriasis. The fact that other eye movements are normal suggests that the motor component of CN III, which originates from the motor nucleus of CN III, is unaffected.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 328, 329.","responses":[{"text":"Superior salivatory nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nucleus Ambiguus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Motor nucleus of CN III","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Edinger-Westphal nucleus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Spinal nucleus of CN V","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16179,"text":"A neonate is diagnosed with obstructive hydrocephalus. The parents were counseled and told that this condition is due to the blockage of a conduit between two ventricles of the brain. Which of the following is the most likely conduit obstructed in this case?","explanation":"In a neonate diagnosed with obstructive hydrocephalus, the most likely conduit obstructed is the **aqueduct of Sylvius**, also known as the cerebral aqueduct. This narrow channel connects the third and fourth ventricles of the brain and is a common site of obstruction in obstructive hydrocephalus. Blockage of the cerebral aqueduct leads to the accumulation of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) in the ventricles upstream of the blockage, particularly the lateral and third ventricles, causing their enlargement.\r\n\r\nThe foramen of Monro (connecting the lateral ventricles to the third ventricle), the foramen of Luschka, and the foramen of Magendie (apertures that allow CSF to flow from the fourth ventricle into the subarachnoid space) are other potential sites of obstruction in hydrocephalus, but they are less commonly involved than the cerebral aqueduct in neonatal obstructive hydrocephalus.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 443.","responses":[{"text":"Foramen of Monro","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paired foramen of Luschka","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Foramen of Magendie","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Foramen of Luschka","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aqueduct of Sylvius","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16181,"text":"An unconscious male patient is brought to the emergency room. An MRI of the brain is performed and reveals infarction of the medial surface of the cerebral hemispheres. Which of the following cortical areas is likely to be affected in this case?","explanation":"The **paracentral lobule** is located on the medial surface of the frontal and parietal lobes, straddling the border between these two lobes around the central sulcus. It is involved in motor and sensory processing for the lower extremity, and its involvement in a cerebral infarction could lead to motor and sensory deficits in the contralateral lower limb.\r\n\r\nThe other areas listed, such as the inferior frontal gyrus, middle frontal gyrus, superior temporal gyrus, and superior parietal lobule, are located on the lateral surface of the cerebral hemispheres and would not be primarily affected in an infarction of the medial surface.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 259.","responses":[{"text":"Superior parietal lobule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior temporal gyrus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle frontal gyrus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior frontal gyrus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paracentral lobule","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16182,"text":"A patient suffers from a gunshot wound injuring his spinal cord on the left side. The patient now has loss of pain and temperature sensation on the right side of the body. Which of the following tracts is likely to be affected in this case?","explanation":"In the scenario described, where a gunshot wound has injured the spinal cord on the left side and the patient experiences loss of pain and temperature sensation on the right side of the body, the affected tract is likely the **left lateral spinothalamic tract**. The lateral spinothalamic tract carries pain and temperature sensations. Crucially, these fibers decussate (cross over) to the opposite side in the spinal cord shortly after entering. Therefore, damage to the spinal cord on the left side would affect the fibers that have crossed over from the right side of the body, leading to loss of pain and temperature sensation on the right side.\r\n\r\nThe dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway, which carries vibration and proprioceptive sensations, and the anterior spinothalamic tract, which carries light touch sensation, are not primarily involved in conveying pain and temperature sensations and therefore are less likely to be the affected tracts in this case.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 143,144.","responses":[{"text":"Left anterior spinothalamic tract","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left lateral spinothalamic tract","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsal column medial lemniscus pathway","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right lateral spinothalamic tract","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right anterior spinothalamic tract","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16183,"text":"A cross-section of the cerebellum shows the cerebellar nuclei embedded in the white matter which is surrounded by the cortex. Which of the following nuclei is located most medially?","explanation":"The cerebellar nuclei are arranged medially to laterally in the following order: fastigial, globose, emboliform, and dentate. The **fastigial nucleus** is the most medial and is associated with the regulation of muscle tone and balance. The dentate nucleus, which is the largest and most lateral, is involved in the planning and initiation of voluntary movements. The globose and emboliform nuclei, also known as the interposed nuclei (when considered together), play a role in motor coordination. The putamen is not a cerebellar nucleus but a part of the basal ganglia involved in motor control and is located in the cerebral hemispheres.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 233.","responses":[{"text":"Emboliform","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Globose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dentate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Putamen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fastigial","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16184,"text":"During a lecture on the basal nuclei, the professor mentions a part of the corpus striatum which is associated with the lateral ventricle medially and the internal capsule laterally. Which of the following structures of the corpus striatum is being mentioned?","explanation":"The **caudate nucleus** forms a key component of the basal nuclei and is closely associated with the lateral ventricle medially and the internal capsule laterally. This anatomical positioning is distinctive for the caudate nucleus and helps differentiate it from other structures of the corpus striatum. \r\n\r\nThe putamen, another part of the corpus striatum, is positioned more laterally and does not share the same relationship with the lateral ventricle. The claustrum, although close to the putamen, is not considered part of the basal nuclei. The globus pallidus, situated medial to the putamen, forms part of the lentiform nucleus and lacks the mentioned association with the lateral ventricle. Lastly, the amygdaloid nucleus, part of the limbic system, is located in the temporal lobe and not directly associated with the lateral ventricle and internal capsule in the same way as the caudate nucleus.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 311.","responses":[{"text":"Caudate nucleus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Globus pallidus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Claustrum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Putamen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amygdaloid nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16185,"text":"The two parietal bones form the sides and the roof of the skull and articulate with each other in the midline. Which of the following sutures is present between these bones?","explanation":"The suture present between the two parietal bones at the midline of the skull is the **sagittal suture**. This suture runs anteroposteriorly along the midline, connecting the left and right parietal bones. It's a key landmark in cranial anatomy, named for its alignment with the sagittal plane, which divides the body into right and left halves. \r\n\r\nThe lambdoid suture articulates with the occipital bone posteriorly, while the coronal suture is located anteriorly, joining the parietal bones to the frontal bone. The squamous suture is found on each side of the skull, marking the boundary between the parietal and temporal bones. Lastly, the sphenofrontal suture, less commonly referred to in basic anatomy, involves the connection between the sphenoid and frontal bones.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 190.","responses":[{"text":"Sphenofrontal suture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coronal suture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lambdoid suture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sagittal suture","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Squamous suture","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16186,"text":"Within the cerebellar cortex, a basket-like nest is formed around the soma of which of the following cells?","explanation":"In the cerebellar cortex, a \"basket-like nest\" is formed around the soma (cell body) of **Purkinje cells**. This unique structure is created by the axonal processes of basket cells. Basket cells are a type of inhibitory interneuron found in the cerebellar cortex. Their axons extend to form complex, basket-like networks around the cell bodies of Purkinje cells. This arrangement is crucial for modulating the activity of the Purkinje cells, which are the principal output neurons of the cerebellar cortex. \r\n\r\nGranule cells, the most numerous neurons in the brain, are found in the granular layer and give rise to parallel fibers. Stellate cells, also in the cerebellum, synapse onto Purkinje cell dendrites but do not form baskets. Pyramidal cells are characteristic of the cerebral cortex, not the cerebellum, and have no such basket formation around them.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 111.","responses":[{"text":"Basket cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stellate cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Granule cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyramidal cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Purkinje cells","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16187,"text":"The cerebellar cortex is composed of three layers. Which of the following layers is a synaptic zone that is mainly composed of dendritic arborizations of Purkinje cells?","explanation":"The **molecular layer** is the most superficial of the three layers of the cerebellar cortex and is characterized by its sparse cellularity but dense network of neural processes. The molecular layer contains the extensive, elaborately branched dendritic trees of Purkinje cells, which receive synaptic inputs from numerous sources, including climbing fibers and parallel fibers. The parallel fibers, which are the axons of granule cells from the granular cell layer, run perpendicular to the Purkinje cell dendrites, forming numerous synaptic connections. This intricate arrangement facilitates the complex integrative functions of the cerebellum in coordinating motor activity and maintaining balance and muscle tone. \r\n\r\nThe other layers, the Purkinje cell layer and the granular cell layer, have distinct roles and cellular compositions, with the Purkinje cell layer containing the cell bodies of Purkinje cells and the granular cell layer being densely packed with granule cells. The pyramidal cell layer is not a part of the cerebellar cortex but is found in the cerebral cortex, and the thalamus is a separate brain structure not part of the cerebellar cortex layers.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 110.","responses":[{"text":"Pyramidal cell layer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thalamus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Purkinje cell layer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Granular cell layer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Molecular layer","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16188,"text":"During the development of the spinal cord, the central canal is lined by three layers. Which of the three layers contains cell bodies of neurons?","explanation":"During the development of the spinal cord, it is the **mantle layer** that contains the cell bodies of neurons. In the embryonic development of the neural tube, which eventually forms the spinal cord, three primary layers are established. The innermost layer is the ventricular layer, which lines the central canal and consists of neural stem cells that divide and give rise to neurons and glial cells. The mantle layer is the intermediate layer, where these newly formed neurons migrate to and differentiate. This layer becomes the gray matter of the spinal cord, characterized by the presence of neuronal cell bodies, dendrites, and unmyelinated axons. The outermost layer is the marginal layer, which primarily comprises the processes of neurons, including myelinated axons, and forms the white matter of the spinal cord. The ependymal layer refers to the lining of the central canal by ependymal cells in the mature spinal cord. The alar plate is a specific region of the neural tube that differentiates into sensory neurons, but it is not a layer lining the central canal.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 315.","responses":[{"text":"Ependymal layer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Marginal layer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alar plate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mantle layer","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular layer","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16189,"text":"During the 5th week of development, five brain swellings appear. These include the telencephalon, diencephalon, mesencephalon, metencephalon, and myelencephalon. The mesencephalon gives rise to which of the following structures?","explanation":"The mesencephalon, one of the five primary brain swellings that appear during the 5th week of embryonic development, gives rise to the **midbrain**. This structure is a component of the brainstem, located between the forebrain and the hindbrain. It plays a critical role in motor movement, particularly movements of the eye, and in auditory and visual processing.\r\n\r\nThe cerebrum arises from the telencephalon, the cerebellum and pons develop from the metencephalon, and the medulla originates from the myelencephalon.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 490.","responses":[{"text":"Cerebellum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pons","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medulla","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Midbrain","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cerebrum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16193,"text":"The speed of a nerve impulse is independent of which of the following factors?","explanation":"The speed of a nerve impulse is independent of the **length of the nerve fiber**. Instead, the speed is largely dependent on the presence of myelin, the diameter of the nerve fiber, and the physiological condition of the nerve.\r\n\r\nMyelin, produced by neurolemmocytes (Schwann cells) in the peripheral nervous system, acts as an insulator and enables faster conduction of impulses through saltatory conduction. The diameter of the nerve fiber also plays a significant role; larger diameter fibers conduct impulses faster due to lower internal resistance. The physiological condition of the nerve, such as its metabolic health and ion channel functionality, also affects impulse speed.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, the length of the nerve fiber does not directly influence the speed of impulse transmission. While longer nerves take more time to conduct an impulse from one end to the other, this is due to the greater distance the impulse must travel, not a change in the speed of conduction. Understanding these factors is crucial in neuroanatomy and neurophysiology for comprehending nerve function and the basis of nerve conduction studies.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 46, 47.","responses":[{"text":"Diameter of nerve fiber","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Physiological condition of the nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Presence of myelin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Presence of neurolemmocyte","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Length of nerve fiber","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16197,"text":"A 20-year-old male was walking barefoot when he suddenly withdrew his leg when he accidentally stepped on a nail. Which of the following reflexes is responsible for activating the antagonistic contralateral extensor muscles in this case?","explanation":"The **crossed extensor reflex** is a crucial component of the body's response to pain and helps maintain balance during unexpected disturbances.\r\n\r\nWhen the individual stepped on the nail, pain receptors (nociceptors) in the foot were activated, initiating the withdrawal reflex, which involves flexing the affected limb away from the painful stimulus. Simultaneously, the crossed extensor reflex is activated in the contralateral (opposite) limb. This reflex involves the extension of the opposite limb to support the body as the injured limb is withdrawn. This is achieved through a complex neural circuit in the spinal cord, where interneurons transmit signals to activate extensor muscles in the opposite limb while inhibiting the flexor muscles.\r\n\r\nThe Babinski and plantar reflexes involve responses to stimulation of the sole of the foot, the stretch reflex involves muscle contraction in response to stretching, and the visceral reflex pertains to the autonomic responses of internal organs.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 693.","responses":[{"text":"Crossed extensor reflex","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Plantar reflex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stretch reflex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Babinski reflex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Visceral reflex","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16200,"text":"During a study, the response of a particular reflex is inhibited for a while and then released suddenly, resulting in a response that is stronger than normal. This is known as which of the following properties of a reflex?","explanation":"This phenomenon is known as the **rebound phenomenon**. It occurs when the response of a reflex is temporarily inhibited and then released, leading to a stronger than normal reflex response. This effect can be understood as a form of physiological compensation. When a reflex is inhibited, the neuronal circuits involved may become more sensitive or primed. Upon release of the inhibition, these primed circuits respond more vigorously, resulting in an exaggerated reflex response.\r\n\r\nSummation refers to the additive effect of multiple stimuli on a reflex, reciprocal innervation involves the simultaneous activation of one muscle group and inhibition of the antagonist muscle group, and central delay describes the time taken for processing in the central nervous system. Habituation refers to the decrease in response to a repeated benign stimulus.","reference":"Angel RW. The rebound phenomenon of gordon holmes. Archives of Neurology. Published April 1, 1977. Accessed June 20, 2023. https://doi.org/10.1001/archneur.1977.00500160064012","responses":[{"text":"Central delay","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rebound phenomenon","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Habituation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Summation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reciprocal innervation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16203,"text":"A 55-year-old male presented to the neurology clinic with the complaint of excessive daytime sleepiness. He was advised to undergo a sleep study. Just after midnight, the lab technician notices the EEG wave showing K complexes and sleep spindles. Which of the following stages of sleep is the patient in at that moment?","explanation":"The patient is in **Stage 2 (N2) of NREM sleep**, as indicated by the presence of K complexes and sleep spindles on the EEG. \r\n\r\nK complexes are single, large amplitude waves that stand out against the background EEG activity. They are often triggered by external stimuli but can also occur spontaneously. Sleep spindles, on the other hand, are bursts of rapid, rhythmic brain wave activity. Both K complexes and sleep spindles are hallmarks of Stage 2 NREM sleep and are believed to play roles in sleep-based memory consolidation and maintaining tranquil sleep despite external disturbances.\r\n\r\nStage 1 (N1) of NREM sleep is a light sleep stage and does not feature K complexes or sleep spindles. Stage 3 (N3) of NREM sleep, also known as slow-wave sleep, is characterized by delta waves and is the deepest sleep stage. REM sleep, known for rapid eye movements and vivid dreaming, also does not exhibit K complexes or sleep spindles.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 508.","responses":[{"text":"Stage 3 (N3) of NREM sleep","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stages 1-3 of NREM sleep","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stage 4 REM sleep","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stage 2 (N2) of NREM sleep","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stage 1 (N1) of NREM sleep","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16205,"text":"Which of the following neurotransmitters is released by the Raphe neurons nerve endings is associated with the induction of sleep?","explanation":"The neurotransmitter released by the Raphe neurons and associated with the induction of sleep is **serotonin**. The Raphe nuclei, located in the brainstem, are a primary source of serotonin in the brain. This neurotransmitter plays a critical role in regulating sleep-wake cycles, mood, and appetite, among other functions.\r\n\r\nSerotonin has been shown to promote sleep by influencing various brain areas involved in sleep regulation. It helps in the transition from wakefulness to sleep and is involved in the regulation of REM (rapid eye movement) sleep. Unlike norepinephrine and dopamine, which are typically associated with wakefulness and arousal, serotonin exerts a more calming effect. GABA, another inhibitory neurotransmitter, is also involved in sleep induction, but it is not primarily released by Raphe neurons. Acetylcholine is linked to REM sleep and wakefulness rather than sleep induction.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 754.","responses":[{"text":"Dopamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetylcholine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Norepinephrine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GABA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serotonin","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16207,"text":"Which of the following parts of the cerebellum is involved in the planning of sequential movements?","explanation":"The cerebellum is divided into several distinct zones, each with specific functions related to movement and coordination. The **lateral zone,** also known as the cerebrocerebellum, is primarily involved in the planning and timing of movements, particularly complex and sequential motor actions.\r\n\r\nThis zone receives input from the cerebral cortex and sends feedback to the motor and premotor cortices, thus playing a crucial role in the cognitive aspect of motor control. It is essential for the coordination of precise, skilled movements and for the smooth execution of sequences of movements.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, the vermis and intermediate zone, which together comprise the spinocerebellum, are more involved in regulating body and limb movements, respectively. The flocculonodular lobe, another part of the cerebellum, is mainly concerned with balance and eye movements.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 712.","responses":[{"text":"Spinocerebellum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intermediate zone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flocculonodular lobe","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vermis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral zone","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16209,"text":"Which of the following cerebellar disorders results in an inability to combine the various components of a movement to create a smooth action?","explanation":"**Asynergia** condition is characterized by a lack of coordination between different muscle groups that are required to perform a single, smooth, and coordinated movement.\r\n\r\nIn asynergia, movements become disjointed and appear broken down into their component parts, rather than being executed as one fluid motion. This lack of coordination is often due to cerebellar dysfunction, as the cerebellum plays a critical role in the timing and force of muscle contractions needed for smooth and coordinated movements.\r\n\r\nDysmetria refers to the inability to judge distance or scale, resulting in over or under-reaching. Dysdiadochokinesia is the inability to perform rapid, alternating movements. Ataxia is a more general term for lack of muscle coordination, which can affect various movements and gait. Asthenia refers to generalized muscle weakness, not specifically linked to cerebellar coordination.","reference":"Fahn S. Movement disorders: overview. Encyclopedia of Movement Disorders. Published March 25, 2010. Accessed June 20, 2023. \r\ndoi:10.1016/B978-0-12-374105-9.00353-1","responses":[{"text":"Asynergia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ataxia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dysmetria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Asthenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dysdiadochokinesia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16229,"text":"Which of the following nuclei of the basal ganglia receives input from the sub-thalamus via the indirect pathway?","explanation":"The **globus pallidus internus** is the nucleus of the basal ganglia that receives input from the sub-thalamus via the indirect pathway. \r\n\r\nIn the basal ganglia circuitry, the indirect pathway serves to inhibit unwanted movements. The sub-thalamus, also known as the subthalamic nucleus, plays a crucial role in this pathway. When there's an intention to suppress a particular movement, the sub-thalamus is activated. It then sends excitatory signals to the globus pallidus externus, which in turn inhibits the globus pallidus internus. This inhibition of the globus pallidus internus reduces its inhibitory influence on the thalamus. Consequently, the thalamus is allowed to exert a more significant excitatory influence on the motor cortex, facilitating the desired motor activity while inhibiting unwanted movements.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 512.","responses":[{"text":"Substantia niagra","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lentiform nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Caudate nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Globus pallidus internus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Putamen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16230,"text":"A 66-year-old male patient suffers from a cerebrovascular accident resulting in a complete loss of sensation on the right side of the body sparing the head and face. Which of the following nuclei of the thalamus is most likely to be affected by this lesion?","explanation":"The **ventral posterolateral (VPL) nucleus** of the thalamus is responsible for relaying sensory information from the body, including touch, pain, and temperature sensations, to the cerebral cortex. It receives input primarily from the contralateral (opposite side) side of the body.\r\n\r\nIn the scenario described, where the right side of the body has lost sensation, it suggests damage or a lesion in the left thalamus, specifically affecting the VPL nucleus responsible for relaying sensory input from the right side of the body. Importantly, the head and face sensations are typically relayed by different thalamic nuclei, such as the ventral posteromedial (VPM) nucleus for the face.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 509.","responses":[{"text":"Ventral anterior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventral posterolateral","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventral lateral","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventral posteromedial","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral geniculate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16231,"text":"Which of the following brain waves are most likely to be present in the EEG of a healthy sleeping person and a brain-damaged awake person?","explanation":"**Delta waves** are characterized by their slow frequency and high amplitude. They typically appear in deep sleep, known as slow-wave sleep (SWS), and during certain stages of non-REM (rapid eye movement) sleep. Delta waves indicate a state of profound relaxation and reduced activity in the brain. In a healthy individual, they are commonly seen during deep sleep stages, signifying restorative and restful sleep.\r\n\r\nIn the context of a brain-damaged awake person, the presence of delta waves could indicate significant neurological impairment. Delta waves in an awake individual are abnormal and may suggest brain dysfunction, such as damage to the brain's regulatory mechanisms or altered consciousness.\r\n\r\nThe other brain waves listed, such as alpha waves (associated with relaxation and wakefulness), beta waves (related to active mental concentration), theta waves (common during drowsiness and light sleep), and gamma waves (associated with information processing), are less likely to be present simultaneously in both a healthy sleeping person and a brain-damaged awake person.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 756.","responses":[{"text":"Alpha waves","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gamma waves","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta waves","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Theta waves","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Delta waves","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16237,"text":"A 40-year-old woman suffers from a cut injuring a peripheral nerve. The distance between the two ends of the damaged nerve is less than 3 mm. Which of the following cells is responsible for the regeneration of this nerve?","explanation":"**Schwann cells** are a vital component of the peripheral nervous system (PNS) and play a crucial role in nerve regeneration. When a peripheral nerve is injured, Schwann cells become activated. They proliferate and form structures known as \"bands of Büngner\" in the distal portion of the damaged nerve. These bands provide a supportive environment for the regenerating axons to grow across the injury site.\r\n\r\nSchwann cells also assist in remyelinating the regenerating axons, ensuring that the nerve signals can be conducted effectively once the regeneration process is complete. This regenerative capacity is a unique feature of the peripheral nervous system and is distinct from the central nervous system, where oligodendrocytes are responsible for myelination but lack the same regenerative capabilities as Schwann cells.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 107.","responses":[{"text":"Oligodendrocyte","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ependymal cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Microglia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Astrocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Schwaan cells","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16240,"text":"A neurologist plans to conduct a study on the properties of sensory neurons. Which of the following types of neurons is most appropriate for this study?","explanation":"**Unipolar neurons,** also known as pseudounipolar neurons, are a specific type of sensory neuron commonly found in the peripheral nervous system. They have a single process that extends from the cell body and then splits into two branches - one leading to sensory receptors in the periphery (e.g., skin, muscles) and the other extending towards the central nervous system (CNS). This unique structure allows them to transmit sensory information from peripheral receptors directly to the CNS.\r\n\r\nAs sensory neurons are primarily responsible for detecting and transmitting sensory stimuli, studying unipolar neurons would provide valuable insights into how sensory information is gathered, transmitted, and processed in the nervous system.\r\n\r\nBipolar neurons are often involved in special sensory functions such as vision and olfaction, while multipolar neurons are typically motor neurons or interneurons involved in complex neural circuits. Motor neurons are responsible for controlling muscle movements and would not be the ideal choice for a study focused on sensory properties.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 33,34.","responses":[{"text":"Motor neurons","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bipolar neurons","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Multipolar neurons","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Unipolar neurons","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Interneurons","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16248,"text":"A 2-year-old boy developed flaccid paralysis after being infected with poliovirus. Poliovirus enters the central nervous system from peripheral nerves and reaches the soma by retrograde transport. Which of the following proteins is used by the virus to reach the cell body?","explanation":"Poliovirus reaches the cell body in infected neurons by retrograde transport, a process that relies on the molecular machinery within neurons. To facilitate this retrograde transport, the virus uses the motor protein **dynein**.\r\n\r\nDynein is a motor protein that moves along microtubules within the neuronal axon, carrying cargoes towards the cell body (soma). In the case of poliovirus infection, after entering peripheral nerves, the virus needs to travel along the neuron's axon to reach the soma within the central nervous system (CNS). Dynein, as the retrograde motor protein, facilitates this movement by attaching to the virus particles and \"walking\" them along the microtubule tracks towards the cell body.","reference":"Mueller S, Cao X, Welker R, Wimmer E. Interaction of the poliovirus receptor cd155 with the dynein light chain tctex-1 and its implication for poliovirus pathogenesis. Journal of Biological Chemistry. Published March 2002. Accessed June 21, 2023. https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0021925819363811","responses":[{"text":"Kinesin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Synaptobrevin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Synaptotagmin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Syntaxin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dynein","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16251,"text":"In an experimental lab, multiple stimuli from different neurons are applied to a post-synaptic neuron simultaneously to generate an action potential. Which one of the following phenomena of a synapse is displayed here?","explanation":"**Spatial summation** occurs when multiple presynaptic neurons release neurotransmitters onto the same post-synaptic neuron at the same time or in rapid succession. These neurotransmitters, when binding to their receptors on the post-synaptic neuron, produce graded potentials. If the combined effect of these graded potentials reaches the threshold for an action potential, the post-synaptic neuron will generate an action potential.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 592, 594.","responses":[{"text":"Presynaptic inhibition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Divergence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spatial summation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Convergence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Temporal summation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16252,"text":"Which of the following types of inhibition is mediated by inhibitory interneurons in the spinal cord and tends to produce the effect of lateral inhibition?","explanation":"**Renshaw cells** are specialized inhibitory interneurons located within the spinal cord. They have the unique ability to inhibit alpha motor neurons, which are responsible for controlling muscle contraction. When activated, Renshaw cells release inhibitory neurotransmitters onto neighboring alpha motor neurons, effectively reducing their activity.\r\n\r\nLateral inhibition, in the context of Renshaw cells, occurs when a sensory input excites certain alpha motor neurons while simultaneously activating Renshaw cells. The Renshaw cells inhibit the neighboring alpha motor neurons, reducing their activity and enhancing the contrast between the activated and non-activated motor neurons. This selective inhibition helps refine motor control and contributes to the precision of movement.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 686.","responses":[{"text":"Presynaptic inhibition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renshaw cell inhibition","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Reciprocal inhibition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Postsynaptic inhibition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Indirect inhibition","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16254,"text":"A 42-year-old jackhammer operator presents in the neurology clinic with decreased sensitivity to high-frequency vibrations in the non-hairy skin of his hands. Which of the following receptors is most likely affected in this case?","explanation":"**Pacinian corpuscles,** also known as lamellated corpuscles, are specialized mechanoreceptors found in the skin and other tissues. They are particularly sensitive to rapid changes in mechanical pressure, making them well-suited for detecting high-frequency vibrations. When mechanical vibrations or pressure waves reach the Pacinian corpuscles, the layers of their membrane (lamellae) are deformed, leading to the generation of nerve impulses that signal the sensation of vibration.\r\n\r\nIn the case of the jackhammer operator, prolonged exposure to the vibrations generated by the jackhammer may have led to the desensitization or damage of these Pacinian corpuscles, resulting in decreased sensitivity to high-frequency vibrations.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 600.","responses":[{"text":"Ruffini endings","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hair sensory fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pacinian corpuscles","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Merkel discs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Free nerve endings","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16350,"text":"The brain can distinguish between the strengths of light touch and sustained pressure during sensory encoding. Which of the following properties is responsible for this action of the brain?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 599.","responses":[{"text":"Type of stimulus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Frequency of action potential","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Location of receptor","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Duration of stimulus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Area of receptive field","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16355,"text":"A 32-year-old male presents to the emergency department with head trauma after he fell from a ladder. A physician shines a flashlight into the patient's eyes and observes that the pupillary reflexes are normal. This reflex is used to test the functioning of which of the following structures of the brain?","explanation":"The pupillary reflex, also known as the pupillary light reflex, is a vital neurological examination to assess the integrity of the visual pathways and **the midbrain's functioning.** When a bright light is directed into one eye, the pupillary reflex causes both pupils to constrict simultaneously. This response occurs through a coordinated interaction between the optic nerve (CN II), the pretectal nucleus in the midbrain, and the oculomotor nerves (CN III) that control the muscles of the pupils.\r\n\r\nIf the pupillary reflex is normal, it indicates that the optic nerves, the pretectal nucleus in the midbrain, and the oculomotor nerves are functioning properly. Any abnormalities in this reflex could suggest damage or dysfunction at various points along this visual pathway, including the midbrain.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 217.","responses":[{"text":"Pons","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothalamus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Midbrain","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Medulla","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Motor cortex","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16358,"text":"The lateral lemniscus is part of a pathway carrying which of the following sensations?","explanation":"The **auditory pathway** is responsible for transmitting sound signals from the ear to the brain, allowing us to perceive and interpret sounds in our environment. The lateral lemniscus is a specific tract within this pathway that plays a crucial role in relaying auditory information from the cochlear nuclei, located in the brainstem, to higher auditory centers in the brain, such as the inferior colliculus.\r\n\r\nPain is transmitted through the spinothalamic tract, proprioception through the dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway, temperature via various sensory receptors, and touch through a combination of pathways, including the dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway and the spinothalamic tract.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 669.","responses":[{"text":"Temperature","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Touch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Auditory","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proprioception","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16361,"text":"A 72-year-old female patient presents to the outpatient clinic with the complaint of being unable to raise her shoulders and turn her head. Investigations reveal a lesion in the medulla. Which of the following cranial nerves is most likely to be affected by this lesion?","explanation":"The **accessory nerve** controls the trapezius and sternocleidomastoid muscles, both of which are involved in the movement of the head and shoulders. The trapezius muscle plays a significant role in shoulder elevation, while the sternocleidomastoid muscle allows for head rotation.\r\n\r\nA lesion in the medulla can disrupt the pathway of the accessory nerve, leading to weakness or paralysis of these muscles. This can result in difficulty in raising the shoulders and turning the head, as described by the patient.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 353.","responses":[{"text":"Glossopharyngeal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abducens nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypoglossal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accessory nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vagus nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16363,"text":"Which of the following functions of the brain is affected when there is damage to the peri-aqueductal gray area of the midbrain?","explanation":"Damage to the peri-aqueductal gray area of the midbrain primarily affects the function related to **endogenous built-in pain suppression**.\r\n\r\nThe peri-aqueductal gray (PAG) is a region in the midbrain known for its role in modulating pain perception. It contains a network of neurons that can produce powerful pain-relieving effects when activated. These neurons are involved in the body's natural pain control system, contributing to the reduction of pain perception and response during stressful or painful situations.\r\n\r\nStimulation of the PAG can lead to the release of endogenous opioids, such as endorphins, which act on opioid receptors in the brain and spinal cord to suppress pain signals. This mechanism is important for both acute and chronic pain management.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 616, 617.","responses":[{"text":"Arousal and alertness of the cerebral cortex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Control of respiratory movements","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coordination of head and neck movements","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maintenance of postural muscle tone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endogenous built-in pain suppression","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16365,"text":"A 60-year-old male patient is suspected to be suffering from impairment of the otolith organs based on a detailed neurological examination and a CT scan. Which of the following functions is most likely to be disturbed in this case?","explanation":"The otolith organs, which include the utricle and saccule, are responsible for detecting linear acceleration and the orientation of the head concerning gravity. They contain tiny calcium carbonate crystals called otoliths, which move in response to gravitational forces and linear acceleration. This movement is detected by hair cells within the otolith organs, which then send signals to the brain to provide information about the **head's position and movement in relation to gravity**.\r\n\r\nWhen the otolith organs are impaired, as in the case of this patient, individuals may experience difficulties in perceiving their head's orientation with respect to gravity. This can lead to feelings of imbalance, unsteadiness, and disequilibrium when standing, walking, or changing positions, as the brain struggles to interpret the body's spatial orientation correctly.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 705.","responses":[{"text":"Prediction of disequilibrium of body with a sudden turn","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elicitation of the vestibulo-ocular reflex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rotation of head to one side","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Recognition of angular acceleration of head","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Detection of the position of the head with respect to gravity","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16369,"text":"In an animal laboratory, the change in the behavior of a monkey is observed. The monkey has a loss of fear, forgetfulness, and the tendency to place everything in its mouth. Ablation of which of the following structures of the limbic system is the most likely cause for these behavioral changes?","explanation":"The **amygdala** is a crucial structure in the limbic system that plays a central role in processing emotions, particularly fear and emotional memory. Damage or ablation of the amygdala can lead to a loss of fear responses, as the amygdala is responsible for evaluating potential threats in the environment and generating appropriate fear responses.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, the amygdala is involved in emotional memory consolidation. Damage to the amygdala can result in forgetfulness and an inability to form or recall emotional memories.\r\n\r\nThe tendency to place everything in its mouth may be related to changes in emotional regulation and impulse control, which can be influenced by amygdala dysfunction.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 306.","responses":[{"text":"Cingulate gyrus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothalamus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prefrontal cortex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hippocampus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amygdala","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16370,"text":"A 45-year-old male presented to a neurology clinic with complaints of spontaneous and continuous writhing movement of hands, an arm, and face. MRI scans reveal a lesion of the globus pallidus. The patient is manifesting which of the following signs in this case?","explanation":"**Athetosis** is a type of involuntary movement disorder characterized by slow, writhing, and continuous movements that affect various parts of the body, including the hands, face, and sometimes other limbs. These movements are often more pronounced during rest and can be exacerbated by emotional stress.\r\n\r\nThe globus pallidus is a part of the basal ganglia, a group of structures involved in motor control and coordination. Damage or dysfunction of the globus pallidus can lead to disruptions in the regulation of muscle tone and movement, resulting in the characteristic athetoid movements.\r\n\r\nThe other movement disorders listed, such as hemiballismus (sudden, violent, and flinging movements), chorea (rapid, jerky, and irregular movements), nystagmus (involuntary eye movements), and Parkinson's disease (characterized by tremors, rigidity, and bradykinesia), have distinct clinical presentations and are associated with different brain regions or pathways.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 721.","responses":[{"text":"Parkinson's disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nystagmus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Athetosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chorea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemiballismus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16371,"text":"The myelin sheath of the neurons is altered due to the formation of plaques in which of the following disorders of the nervous system?","explanation":"**Multiple sclerosis** is an autoimmune neurological disorder in which the body's immune system mistakenly attacks and damages the myelin sheath, the protective covering that surrounds nerve fibers in the central nervous system (CNS). These immune-mediated attacks result in the formation of plaques or lesions within the CNS, disrupting the normal transmission of nerve impulses.\r\n\r\nAs the myelin sheath is damaged, the nerve impulses are slowed down or blocked, leading to a wide range of neurological symptoms, including muscle weakness, coordination difficulties, sensory disturbances, and sometimes cognitive impairments. The exact cause of MS is not fully understood, but it is believed to involve a combination of genetic and environmental factors.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 188.","responses":[{"text":"Epilepsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Parkinson's disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cerebral palsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neurosyphilis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Multiple sclerosis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16373,"text":"Which of the following cranial nerves are a part of the parasympathetic nervous system?","explanation":"The cranial nerves that are part of the **parasympathetic nervous system** include cranial nerves **III (oculomotor), VII (facial), IX (glossopharyngeal), and X (vagus)**.\r\n\r\nThese cranial nerves contain parasympathetic fibers that innervate various target organs, promoting rest-and-digest functions and helping to maintain homeostasis in the body.\r\n\r\n**Cranial nerve III (oculomotor)** contains parasympathetic fibers that innervate the ciliary muscle for accommodation of the lens and the sphincter pupillae muscle for constriction of the pupil.\r\n\r\n- **Cranial nerve VII (facial)** contains parasympathetic fibers that stimulate the submandibular and sublingual salivary glands and lacrimal glands for tear production.\r\n\r\n**Cranial nerve IX (glossopharyngeal)** contains parasympathetic fibers that stimulate the parotid salivary gland.\r\n\r\n**Cranial nerve X (vagus)** contains the majority of parasympathetic fibers in the cranial nerves and innervates various thoracic and abdominal organs, including the heart, lungs, and digestive organs, to regulate functions such as heart rate, bronchoconstriction, and gastrointestinal activity.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 390.","responses":[{"text":"III, V, IX, and X","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"III, IV, VII, and IX","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"V, IX, X, and XII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IV, V, IX, and X","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"III, VII, IX, and X","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16378,"text":"Before a minor surgical procedure, a local anesthetic is injected by the surgeon to ensure that the patient feels no pain. Which of the following nerve fibers is most likely to be blocked by the local anesthetic?","explanation":"In the context of local anesthesia, the administration of a local anesthetic typically blocks nerve fibers in a specific sequence.\r\n\r\n**C-type fibers** are the first to be blocked. These fibers are unmyelinated and are responsible for transmitting autonomic impulses and sensations related to pain. Blocking C fibers results in the relief of pain.\r\n\r\nAfter C fibers, the next to be affected are **B-type fibers**, which are small myelinated fibers. These fibers include preganglionic sympathetic fibers. Blocking B fibers can lead to changes in autonomic function.\r\n\r\nFinally, **A-type fibers** are blocked. These fibers include both large myelinated motor fibers and sensory fibers. Blocking A fibers affects sensations such as proprioception, touch, pressure, and motor function.","reference":"Vereecken P, Camargo CLDA. Local anesthesia. Dermatologic Surgery and Procedures.\r\nPublished February 28th, 2018. Accessed June 27th, 2023. doi:10.5772/intechopen.72930","responses":[{"text":"Type B fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A alpha fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type C fibers","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"A beta fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A gamma fibers","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16382,"text":"Which of the following substances is released by interneurons in the dorsal horn of the spinal cord to inhibit ascending pain signals?","explanation":"In the dorsal horn of the spinal cord, the substance released by interneurons to inhibit ascending pain signals is **enkephalin**. Enkephalin is one of the endogenous opioids produced in the body, and it plays a critical role in modulating pain.\r\n\r\nThe dorsal horn of the spinal cord is a key site for the processing and modulation of pain signals. When pain signals reach the dorsal horn, they can be modulated by various neurotransmitters and neuromodulators. Enkephalins, along with other endogenous opioids like endorphins and dynorphins, bind to opioid receptors on the presynaptic and postsynaptic terminals of the pain pathway neurons. This binding inhibits the release of pain neurotransmitters and reduces the activity of pain pathways, thus decreasing the perception of pain.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 617","responses":[{"text":"Serotonin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glutamate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GABA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enkephalin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetylcholine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16567,"text":"During voluntary movements, the Golgi tendon organs are involved in providing which of the following information to the central nervous system?","explanation":"During voluntary movements, the **Golgi tendon organs** provide information to the central nervous system about the **tension developed in the muscle being moved**.\r\n\r\nThe Golgi tendon organs are sensory receptors located within the tendons of skeletal muscles near their attachment to the muscle fibers. Their primary function is to monitor muscle tension or force during muscle contractions. When a muscle contracts, it generates force, and this force is transmitted to the tendon, where the Golgi tendon organs are located.\r\n\r\nThese sensory organs are connected to nerve fibers that transmit signals to the central nervous system. When muscle tension increases during contraction, the Golgi tendon organs are stimulated, and they send signals to the brain to convey information about the level of tension being generated in the muscle.\r\n\r\nThis feedback mechanism is essential for preventing excessive muscle force, as the central nervous system can regulate muscle contraction to avoid potential injury due to overexertion. It helps maintain muscle force within safe limits during voluntary movements.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 690.","responses":[{"text":"Tension developed in the muscle being moved","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Activity of type 1a nerve fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Change in the joint angle produced by movement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Length of the muscle being moved","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Velocity of movement","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16569,"text":"Which of the following hormones or factors is responsible for inhibiting the action of leptin on the ventromedial nucleus of the hypothalamus and stimulating the lateral hypothalamic nucleus producing a sense of hunger?","explanation":"Leptin is a hormone produced by adipose (fat) tissue that signals the brain, particularly the ventromedial nucleus of the hypothalamus, about the body's energy stores. When leptin levels are high, it signifies sufficient energy reserves, leading to reduced appetite and increased energy expenditure.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, **ghrelin** is produced primarily by the stomach and is known as the \"hunger hormone.\" Ghrelin levels rise when the stomach is empty, signaling the brain's lateral hypothalamic nucleus to stimulate hunger and promote food intake.\r\n\r\nGhrelin acts in opposition to leptin; it dampens the effects of leptin on the hypothalamus, effectively promoting hunger even in situations where leptin would normally suppress appetite. This intricate hormonal interplay helps regulate energy balance and maintain appropriate body weight.","reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 880.\r\n\r\n\r\n(2) Abizaid A, Horvath TL. Ghrelin and the central regulation of feeding and energy balance. Indian Journal of Endocrinology and Metabolism. Published December 2012. Accessed July 3, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3602992/","responses":[{"text":"Ghrelin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stretch of the Gastrointestinal tract","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"α-MSH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leptin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16572,"text":"Which of the following mechanisms is involved in the conversion of short-term memory to long-term memory?","explanation":"**Long-term potentiation** is a process by which the strength of synaptic connections between neurons is increased in response to repeated, high-frequency stimulation. It plays a fundamental role in the formation of long-term memories. The following steps are involved in this process:\r\n\r\n1. When neurons are stimulated repeatedly and intensely, such as during learning or memorization, it leads to a change in the synaptic connections between these neurons.\r\n\r\n2. This change involves an increase in the efficiency of synaptic transmission, which means that the postsynaptic neuron becomes more responsive to the signals from the presynaptic neuron.\r\n\r\n3. These strengthened synaptic connections persist over time, allowing for the encoding of information into long-term memory.\r\n\r\nLTP is often associated with specific patterns of neural activity and the activation of NMDA receptors, which are crucial for the changes in synaptic strength. This process ensures that important information is retained and can be recalled in the long term.","reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 738.\r\n  \r\n\r\n(2) Dong Z, Han H, Li H, et al. Long-term potentiation decay and memory loss are mediated by AMPAR endocytosis. The Journal of Clinical Investigation. Published January 2, 2015. Accessed July 3, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4382266/","responses":[{"text":"Post-tetanic potentiation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Circuit of reverberating neurons","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Long-term potentiation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Habituation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sensitization","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16574,"text":"A 45-year-old male patient suffering from a head injury undergoes a neurological examination. The neurologist observes that the patient can understand both spoken and written words but his speech is slow, poorly articulated, and requires significant effort. Which of the following areas of the cerebral cortex is most likely to be damaged in this case?","explanation":"**Broca's area,** located in the left frontal lobe of the cerebral cortex (typically in the dominant hemisphere, which is usually the left hemisphere in right-handed individuals), is responsible for the production of speech. It plays a crucial role in the generation and coordination of the motor movements required for fluent and articulate speech.\r\n\r\nDamage to Broca's area can result in a condition known as **Broca's aphasia** or **non-fluent aphasia**. Patients with Broca's aphasia typically have intact comprehension of spoken and written language (as observed in this case), but they struggle to express themselves verbally. Their speech is characterized by slow, effortful, and poorly articulated sentences. They may have difficulty forming grammatically correct sentences and may use short and telegraphic language.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, damage to **Wernicke's area**, another language-related area in the left hemisphere, typically results in **Wernicke's aphasia**, where patients have fluent but nonsensical speech with impaired comprehension.","reference":"White J, Seiden D. USMLE® Step 1 Lecture Notes 2019: Anatomy. Kaplan Medical; 2019: 350.","responses":[{"text":"Arcuate fasciculus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatosensory area","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Angular gyrus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Wernicke's area","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Broca's area","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16578,"text":"The deficiency of which of the following vitamins is marked by anemia, impaired neurotransmitter production, increased homocysteine levels, and neuronal demyelination?","explanation":"**Vitamin B12 deficiency** is associated with a range of health issues, including anemia, impaired neurotransmitter production, elevated homocysteine levels, and neuronal demyelination. Anemia occurs because Vitamin B12 is crucial for the maturation of red blood cells. In its absence, red blood cells become larger and less functional. Additionally, Vitamin B12 plays a vital role in myelin synthesis, the protective sheath around nerve fibers. When Vitamin B12 is deficient, myelin production is compromised, leading to neuronal demyelination and disruptions in nerve signal transmission. Elevated homocysteine levels result from Vitamin B12's involvement in homocysteine metabolism, contributing to cardiovascular risks and potential nervous system damage.","reference":"(1) Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 380, 381.\r\n\r\n(2) Gilfix BM. Vitamin B12 and homocysteine. CMAJ : Canadian Medical Association Journal. Published November 22, 2005. Accessed July 3, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1283514/","responses":[{"text":"Vitamin B2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B12","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B1","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16580,"text":"Which of the following vitamins is required for the synthesis of neurotransmitters like dopamine, serotonin, and GABA?","explanation":"**Pyridoxine**, also known as **vitamin B6**, is the essential vitamin required for the synthesis of neurotransmitters like dopamine, serotonin, and gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA). \r\n\r\nDopamine is a neurotransmitter associated with mood, reward, and motor control. Serotonin is known for its role in regulating mood, sleep, and appetite. GABA is the primary inhibitory neurotransmitter in the central nervous system, contributing to relaxation and reducing excitability.\r\n\r\nPyridoxine serves as a coenzyme for enzymes involved in the synthesis of these neurotransmitters. For instance, it participates in the conversion of the amino acid tryptophan to serotonin and the conversion of the amino acid tyrosine to dopamine. Additionally, pyridoxine supports the decarboxylation of glutamate to GABA.","reference":"Stover PJ, Field MS. Vitamin B-61. Advances in Nutrition. Published January 7, 2015. Accessed July 3, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4288272/","responses":[{"text":"Thiamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Niacin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyridoxine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Riboflavin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cyanocobalamin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16581,"text":"In the blood-brain barrier, the endothelial cells are tightly packed together by means of tight junctions that are formed by which of the following specialized transmembrane proteins?","explanation":"**Claudins** are a family of proteins that play a crucial role in regulating the permeability of the blood-brain barrier. They are responsible for the tight sealing of adjacent endothelial cells, effectively preventing the passage of most molecules and ions from the bloodstream into the brain tissue. This selective barrier function is essential for maintaining the brain's homeostasis and protecting it from potentially harmful substances.\r\n\r\nUnlike some other proteins like selectins, which are involved in cell adhesion and are more prevalent in processes like inflammation, Claudins are specifically tailored for the establishment and maintenance of the blood-brain barrier's impermeability. Their tight junctions ensure that only essential nutrients and molecules are allowed to cross into the brain while preventing the entry of pathogens and toxins.","reference":"Dow lecture slides. Neuroscience module. Subject: Biochemistry, Topic: Chemical composition of the blood-brain barrier, Sub-topic: Tight junctions.","responses":[{"text":"Glycophorins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Claudins","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Integrins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Selectins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rhodopsins","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16583,"text":"Which of the following compounds crosses the blood-brain barrier by means of receptor-mediated transcytosis?","explanation":"**Insulin** binds to insulin receptors located on the luminal (blood-facing) side of the brain capillary endothelial cells. Once bound to these receptors, insulin is taken up into the endothelial cells through receptor-mediated endocytosis. Inside the cells, insulin-containing vesicles are formed, and these vesicles transport insulin across the endothelial cells. Finally, insulin is released on the abluminal (brain-facing) side of the endothelial cells, allowing it to enter the brain tissue.\r\n\r\nThis mechanism ensures that insulin, a vital hormone involved in glucose regulation and various metabolic processes, can reach the brain, where it plays roles in regulating food intake, energy expenditure, and other important functions. Unlike insulin, glucose crosses the blood-brain barrier through facilitated diffusion, while the other compounds listed do not use receptor-mediated transcytosis for transport across the barrier.","reference":"Dow lecture slides. Neuroscience module. Subject: Biochemistry, Topic: Chemical composition of the blood-brain barrier, Sub-topic: BBB Transport systems.","responses":[{"text":"Leucine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Free fatty acids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Insulin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phenylalanine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16584,"text":"Parkinson's disease is associated with the loss of specific neurons containing which of the following neurotransmitters?","explanation":"In Parkinson's disease, there is a progressive degeneration of **dopaminergic neurons** in a specific brain region called the **substantia nigra**. These neurons are responsible for producing and releasing dopamine, a crucial neurotransmitter that plays a central role in motor control and coordination.\r\n\r\nThis dopamine deficiency results in the characteristic motor symptoms of the disease, including tremors, bradykinesia (slowness of movement), rigidity, and postural instability.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 286.","responses":[{"text":"Dopamine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"GABA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Indolamines","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serotonin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Norepinephrine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16585,"text":"A cobweb coagulum is a characteristic finding on CSF examination in which of the following conditions?","explanation":"**Tuberculous meningitis** is a form of meningitis caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis, the same bacterium responsible for tuberculosis (TB). When this infection involves the meninges, it can lead to the formation of the cobweb-like coagulum in the CSF. This coagulum is composed of fibrin strands and is a distinct feature seen in the CSF of patients with tuberculous meningitis.","reference":"James J, Kunju P. Central nervous system tuberculosis in children. Pediatric Infectious Disease. Published March 2019. Accessed July 3, 2023. https://www.pidjournal.com/doi/10.5005/jp-journals-10081-1106","responses":[{"text":"Viral meningitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subarachnoid hemorrhage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bacterial meningitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brain tumour","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tuberculous meningitis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16592,"text":"A 39-year-old female patient presents to the outpatient department with a severe headache for the last 3 days. On physical examination, she is afebrile and normotensive. Fundoscopic examination shows papilledema in the right eye. She was admitted to the hospital for further testing. A day later, she develops right pupillary dilation with impaired ocular movement. These findings are best explained by which of the following lesions?","explanation":"**Transtentorial herniation** occurs when there is an increase in intracranial pressure, leading to the displacement of brain structures through the tentorial notch, a small opening in the membrane called the tentorium cerebelli that separates the cerebrum from the cerebellum. \r\n\r\nIn this specific case, the **uncus of the medial temporal lobe** herniates through the tentorial notch. This herniation compresses the **oculomotor nerve (cranial nerve III)** and causes dilation of the right pupil (mydriasis) due to the parasympathetic fibers of the oculomotor nerve being affected. Additionally, the pressure on adjacent structures impairs ocular movement, leading to deficits in eye movement.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1255.","responses":[{"text":"Subdural hematoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transtentorial medial temporal herniation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Frontal lobe abscess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ruptured berry aneurysm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrocephalus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16593,"text":"A female infant born after a full-term pregnancy weighing 3.4kg has an enlarged head with the occipitofrontal circumference (OFC) being 49.5 cm. A cranial ultrasound reveals bilateral ventriculomegaly. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Hydrocephalus** is a condition characterized by the accumulation of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) within the brain's ventricles, leading to an increase in intracranial pressure and enlargement of the head. \r\n\r\nBilateral ventriculomegaly, as revealed by cranial ultrasound, further supports the diagnosis. Ventriculomegaly refers to the dilation or enlargement of the brain's ventricles, which are fluid-filled spaces within the brain. This dilation is often seen in hydrocephalus due to the impaired circulation or absorption of CSF.\r\n\r\nEncephalitis and meningitis are typically associated with signs of infection, such as fever and irritability, which are not described in this case. Cerebral edema and herniation would not typically present as isolated findings in an infant but could result from severe untreated hydrocephalus if intracranial pressure remains elevated.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 181.","responses":[{"text":"Hydrocephalus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Herniation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Encephalitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Meningitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cerebral edema","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16598,"text":"A 35-year-old male who has a history of HIV is admitted to the neurology ward with signs and symptoms of encephalitis. Which of the following is a characteristic histopathological finding of HIV encephalitis?","explanation":"Histologically, the brain tissue in HIV encephalitis often shows the presence of **microglial nodules**, which are clusters of activated microglial cells. Microglial cells are the brain's resident immune cells, and their activation is a response to HIV infection within the brain.\r\n\r\nIn addition to microglial nodules, another hallmark finding in HIV encephalitis is the presence of **multinucleated giant cells**. These cells are formed by the fusion of infected microglial cells and are a distinctive feature of HIV-associated brain pathology.\r\n\r\nGliosis, characterized by the proliferation of glial cells in response to injury or infection, can also be present in HIV encephalitis. However, it is not as specific as the presence of microglial nodules and multinucleated giant cells in the diagnosis of this condition.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1278.","responses":[{"text":"Microglial nodules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophilia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Microglial nodules and multinucleated giant cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gliosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophil infiltration","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16600,"text":"Which of the following is not a risk factor for encephalitis?","explanation":"**People with a strong immune system** are not typically considered a risk factor for encephalitis. Encephalitis is an inflammatory condition of the brain usually caused by viral infections. \r\n\r\nRisk factors for encephalitis often involve conditions or situations that can either weaken the immune system or increase exposure to potential pathogens. Individuals with weakened immune systems, such as those with HIV/AIDS or undergoing immunosuppressive therapy, are at higher risk because their immune system may have difficulty controlling viral infections. Older individuals may have a weaker immune response, making them more susceptible to infections, including encephalitis. Infants often have developing immune systems, and their immune responses may not be as effective in fighting off infections.","reference":"Dow lecture slides. Neuroscience module. Subject: Pathology, Topic: Encephalitis, Sub-topic: Predisposing factors.","responses":[{"text":"People with a weak immune system","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"People with a strong immune system","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Children under the age of 1 year","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HIV infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Older age","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16602,"text":"A 50-year-old female patient who is a known case of an autoimmune disorder visits the neurology clinic with complaints of fatigue, tingling, numbness, muscle weakness, and muscle spasms. CSF analysis reveals oligoclonal bands. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis in this case?","explanation":"**Multiple sclerosis (MS)** is an autoimmune disorder that primarily affects the central nervous system (CNS), including the brain and spinal cord. It is characterized by the demyelination of nerve fibers, which disrupts the normal flow of electrical impulses along the nerves. The clinical presentation often includes a wide range of neurological symptoms, such as fatigue, tingling, numbness, muscle weakness, and muscle spasms, all of which are consistent with the patient's complaints.\r\n\r\nOne of the diagnostic findings associated with MS is the presence of **oligoclonal bands** in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF). These bands represent abnormal antibodies produced within the CNS, indicating an immune system response in the central nervous system. This finding is supportive of the diagnosis of MS.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 188.","responses":[{"text":"Multiple sclerosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cerebral edema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cerebral herniation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Central pontine myelinolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subdural hematoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16604,"text":"A 5-month-old boy is brought to the outpatient clinic with complaints of global developmental delay, generalized weakness of the body, and jerky eye movement. There is also a family history of his 5-year-old  brother having the same complaints. MRI scans of the brain reveal symmetrical lesions. Genetic studies reveal a mutation in the ABCD1 gene located at the X chromosome. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Adrenoleukodystrophy** is a rare genetic disorder that primarily affects the nervous system and adrenal glands. It is an X-linked recessive disorder, which means that it predominantly affects males and can be passed on by female carriers.\r\n\r\nThe clinical presentation of ALD includes global developmental delay, generalized weakness, and jerky eye movements, which are consistent with the symptoms described in the 5-month-old boy. Furthermore, the presence of symmetrical brain lesions on MRI scans is a characteristic feature of ALD.\r\n\r\nThe mutation in the **ABCD1 gene**, which is located on the X chromosome, is associated with ALD. This gene encodes a peroxisomal membrane protein responsible for the transport of very-long-chain fatty acids. Mutations in the ABCD1 gene result in the accumulation of very-long-chain fatty acids in various tissues, including the brain and adrenal glands, leading to the neurological and adrenal manifestations seen in ALD.","reference":"(1) Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 187.\r\n\r\n(2) Raymond GV, Moser AB, Fatemi A, et al. X-linked adrenoleukodystrophy. GeneReviews®. Published 1993. Accessed July 4, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK1315/","responses":[{"text":"Canavan disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adrenoleukodystrophy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Alexander disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metachromatic leukodystrophy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Multiple sclerosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16606,"text":"A 5-year-old boy is admitted to the neurology ward with complaints of headache, photophobia, and neck rigidity. He is a suspected case of meningitis. Which of the following is the best diagnostic investigation for meningitis?","explanation":"In the case of a suspected meningitis, the most appropriate diagnostic investigation is **CSF analysis** (Cerebrospinal Fluid analysis). Meningitis is characterized by the inflammation of the membranes (meninges) that envelop the brain and spinal cord, often caused by various infectious agents like bacteria, viruses, or fungi. CSF analysis involves the extraction of cerebrospinal fluid through a lumbar puncture (spinal tap). \r\n\r\nCSF analysis is pivotal for several reasons. Firstly, it confirms the diagnosis, indicating whether an infection is present and identifying the causative agent. This information is essential for determining the appropriate treatment, as bacterial and viral meningitis require different therapeutic approaches. Furthermore, CSF analysis helps in evaluating the severity of the condition by examining cell counts, protein levels, and glucose concentrations in the CSF. It also guides the selection of antibiotics or antiviral medications for treatment. Additionally, serial CSF analyses may be performed to monitor the response to treatment and guide the duration of therapy.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 184.","responses":[{"text":"CSF analysis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Urine test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete blood count","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"X-ray","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MRI brain","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16625,"text":"A 1-year-old girl is diagnosed with bacterial meningitis. Which of the following findings in the CSF analysis are suggestive of bacterial meningitis?","explanation":"**100-2000 polymorphs** (neutrophils), as opposed to lymphocytes, in the CSF is a crucial indicator of bacterial meningitis. Neutrophils are the primary white blood cells involved in the body's defense against bacterial infections. Their presence in the CSF suggests an acute inflammatory response, typically seen in bacterial meningitis.","reference":"(1) Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 180.\r\n(2) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020:1272.","responses":[{"text":"Increased glucose content in CSF","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"100-2000 polymorphs","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"No lymphocytes and polymorphs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clear CSF","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"100-500 lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16627,"text":"A young male patient presents to the emergency department in an unconscious state. The parents give a history of him swimming in a pool for the last few days. CSF analysis reveals small flask-shaped amoeba. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis in this case?","explanation":"*Naegleria fowleri* is a free-living amoeba found in warm freshwater environments, such as lakes, rivers, and poorly maintained swimming pools. When contaminated water enters the nasal passages, the amoeba can travel along the olfactory nerve to reach the brain, causing a severe and often fatal infection.\r\n\r\nThe CSF analysis revealing the presence of these amoeba is a characteristic feature of *Naeglaria fowleri* infection, commonly known as primary amoebic meningoencephalitis (PAM). Symptoms typically progress rapidly and include headache, fever, altered mental status, seizures, and coma. Unfortunately, PAM is associated with a high mortality rate, and prompt diagnosis and treatment are essential for any chance of survival.","reference":"Dow lecture slides. Neuroscience module. Subject: Pathology, Topic: Encephalitis, Sub-topic: Naegleria Fowleri.","responses":[{"text":"Naegleria fowleri","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acanthamoeba","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cysticercosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Candida albicans","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prion disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16629,"text":"A 60-year-old male patient with a history of hypertension for the last 10 years is brought to the emergency department in an unconscious state. History also reveals that the patient is non-compliant with his medication for hypertension. MRI and CT scan brain show a lobar hemorrhage. Which of the following is the most likely cause of this condition?","explanation":"**Hypertension,** or high blood pressure, is a well-known risk factor for the development of cerebral hemorrhages, particularly in the lobar regions of the brain. Prolonged and uncontrolled hypertension can lead to structural changes in the walls of small blood vessels in the brain. These changes include arteriolar sclerosis, which involves thickening and narrowing of the blood vessel walls, and hyaline arteriolosclerosis, characterized by the deposition of hyaline material in the vessel walls. These alterations weaken the integrity of the blood vessels, making them more prone to rupture and leading to spontaneous hemorrhages.\r\n\r\nWhile other factors like arteriovenous malformations and trauma can cause intracerebral hemorrhages, the patient's history of uncontrolled hypertension makes it the most likely cause in this scenario. Conditions like diabetes and cerebral amyloid angiopathy can also contribute to hemorrhagic events, but they are less commonly associated with lobar hemorrhages in the context of this patient's presentation.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 186.","responses":[{"text":"Arteriovenous malformation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cerebral amyloid angiopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trauma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertension","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16631,"text":"Which of the following is an inhibitory neurotransmitter that causes hyperpolarization of neurons?","explanation":"**GABA** is one of the most important inhibitory neurotransmitters in the central nervous system (CNS). Its primary role is to reduce neuronal excitability and dampen the transmission of nerve signals. When GABA is released into the synaptic cleft, it binds to specific GABA receptors on the postsynaptic neuron. Activation of these receptors leads to the opening of chloride ion channels in the neuron's membrane. Chloride ions then flow into the neuron, resulting in hyperpolarization. Hyperpolarization makes it more difficult for the neuron to reach its threshold for generating an action potential, effectively inhibiting its firing and reducing neuronal activity.\r\n\r\nThis inhibitory action of GABA is essential for maintaining the balance of excitatory and inhibitory signals in the brain, which is crucial for normal brain function. Imbalances in GABAergic signaling can lead to neurological disorders and conditions such as epilepsy, anxiety disorders, and more.","reference":"Dow lecture slides. Neuroscience module. Subject: Biochemistry, Topic: Introduction and classification of neurotransmitters, Sub-topic: GABA.","responses":[{"text":"Glutamate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"GABA (gamma aminobutyric acid)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetylcholine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Norepinephrine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dopamine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16634,"text":"The analgesic properties of opioids are primarily mediated by which of the following receptors?","explanation":"**Mu (μ) receptors** are one of the main types of opioid receptors found in the central nervous system (CNS) and peripheral tissues. Activation of mu receptors by opioid drugs, such as morphine, codeine, and fentanyl, leads to a series of physiological responses that are responsible for their potent pain-relieving effects.\r\n\r\nWhen opioids bind to mu receptors, they modulate the perception of pain through various mechanisms. First, they inhibit the release of neurotransmitters like substance P, which transmit pain signals in the spinal cord. This reduces the transmission of painful stimuli to the brain. Second, opioids enhance the activity of descending inhibitory pathways, which further suppress the transmission of pain signals. Additionally, activation of mu receptors can lead to the release of endorphins, which are endogenous opioid peptides with natural pain-relieving properties.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 180.","responses":[{"text":"Adrenergic receptor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kappa receptor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mu receptor","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Delta receptor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholinergic receptor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16641,"text":"A 36-year-old man is hired as a laboratory worker and he will be handling Rabies related viruses and vaccines. Which of the following vaccines is he advised to get?","explanation":"Rabies is a deadly viral infection that affects the central nervous system. Laboratory workers who may come into contact with the Rabies virus, even indirectly, are at risk of exposure. **Pre-exposure prophylaxis** involves administering a series of Rabies vaccine doses to individuals before potential exposure to the virus. This prophylactic vaccination helps the immune system develop protective antibodies against the virus.\r\n\r\nThe Rabies vaccine used for pre-exposure prophylaxis is safe and effective. It typically involves a series of three to four doses over a few weeks. Once the full series is completed, individuals are considered to have a certain level of immunity to Rabies, which provides protection in case of accidental exposure.","reference":"Dow lecture slides. Neuroscience module. Subject: Community Medicine, Topic: Rabies, Sub-topic: Immunization of people.","responses":[{"text":"Pre-exposure prophylaxis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"H-RIG (human rabies immunoglobulin)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Post-exposure prophylaxis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"E-RIG (equine rabies immunoglobulin)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tetanus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16643,"text":"A 32-year-old mother of two children visits a primary healthcare center with complaints of feeling sad, irritable, and empty, and often finds herself crying for no reason for the past three months. She has a loss of interest in all activities and finds it really hard to carry out her daily activities. She feels as if she would be better off dead and even has thoughts about taking her life at times. Which one of the following disorders is she most likely suffering from?","explanation":"**Depression,** also known as major depressive disorder (MDD), is a common mental health condition characterized by a persistent low mood and a loss of interest or pleasure in activities that were once enjoyable. People with depression may also experience other symptoms, such as changes in appetite and sleep patterns, fatigue, difficulty concentrating, feelings of worthlessness or guilt, and thoughts of self-harm or suicide.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 580.","responses":[{"text":"Schizophrenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bipolar disorder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Post-traumatic stress disorder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anxiety","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Depression","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16644,"text":"Which of the following terms refers to the constant presence of a disease or infectious agent within its usual or expected frequency in a given geographical area or population group?","explanation":"**Endemic** diseases are those that are consistently present in a particular geographic area or population without the need for external introductions. These diseases have become a natural part of the local environment, and their occurrence is relatively stable over time. In an endemic region, the disease may continue to circulate at a baseline level without causing major outbreaks or unusual spikes in cases.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, **Epidemic** refers to the sudden increase in the number of cases of a disease above what is normally expected in a specific population or geographic area. Epidemics often occur when a new infectious agent is introduced or when existing control measures fail to contain the spread of the disease.\r\n\r\n**Prevalence** is the total number of cases of a disease in a given population at a specific point in time, regardless of when the disease first appeared or how long individuals have had the disease.\r\n\r\n**Incidence** refers to the number of new cases of a disease that occur in a defined population over a specified period, typically a year.\r\n\r\n**Sporadic** describes diseases that occur occasionally and at irregular intervals, with no consistent pattern in terms of time or location. These diseases do not follow a predictable or cyclical pattern of occurrence.","reference":"Dow lecture slides. Neuroscience module. Subject: Community medicine, Topic: Endemic diseases involving the Nervous system, Sub-topic: Endemic diseases.","responses":[{"text":"Sporadic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epidemic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Incidence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prevalence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endemic","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16646,"text":"Polic is now endemic in only 2 countries; Pakistan and Afghanistan. Two very effective polio vaccines, the oral and injectable vaccines are being given in the EPI program, and in addition, special immunization campaigns are repeatedly conducted all over Pakistan to eradicate polio. In the routine EPI schedule, which of the following is the correct age for the administration of the injectable polio vaccine (IPV)?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow lecture slides. Neuroscience module. Subject: Community Medicine, Topic: Polio Eradication, Sub-topic: EPI vaccination schedule.","responses":[{"text":"10 weeks","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"9 months","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"14 weeks and 9 months","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"14 weeks","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"6 weeks","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16647,"text":"John diverts his attention to stop thinking about disturbing events in order to prevent himself from experiencing any overwhelming negative emotions. Which of the following term best corresponds to this strategy?","explanation":"**Antecedent-based strategies** involve taking action before a stressful situation occurs to minimize its impact or prevent it from happening altogether. In John's case, he is proactively avoiding the distressing thoughts or events by diverting his attention. By doing so, he aims to reduce the emotional distress associated with those events.\r\n\r\n**Situation selection** involves choosing to enter or avoid specific situations or environments to minimize exposure to stressors.\r\n\r\n**Cognitive reappraisal** involves changing one's perception or interpretation of a situation to make it less emotionally distressing.\r\n\r\n**Response modulation** pertains to directly managing emotional experiences or expressions in response to a stressful situation.\r\n\r\n**Response-focused strategies** involve managing emotional responses or physiological reactions after they have already occurred.","reference":"Dow lecture slides. Neuroscience module. Subject: Behavioural sciences, Topic: Emotional Intelligence and Managing Emotions, Sub-topic: Antecedent-focused strategies.","responses":[{"text":"Cognitive reappraisal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antecedent based strategies","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Response focused strategies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Situation selection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Response modulation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16648,"text":"During a flood, a mental health professional is given the responsibility to provide psychological first aid and conduct crisis intervention. Which of the following is the 7th and last stage of the crisis intervention model?","explanation":"During crisis intervention, it is crucial to ensure that individuals receive ongoing support and resources beyond the initial crisis intervention. This stage focuses on **planning for the future and establishing a follow-up plan** to ensure the person's continued well-being and recovery.\r\n\r\nThe stages leading up to the last stage include:\r\n\r\n1. **Plan and conduct a crisis intervention:** This is the initial stage where the mental health professional assesses the crisis, ensures safety, and provides immediate support.\r\n\r\n2. **Deal with feelings and emotions:** In this stage, the focus is on helping the individual express and process their emotions related to the crisis.\r\n\r\n3. **Generate and explore alternatives:** Here, the professional and the individual collaboratively explore potential solutions or coping strategies to address the crisis.\r\n\r\n4. **Develop and formulate an action plan:** A concrete plan is developed based on the alternatives explored, with a clear course of action for addressing the crisis.\r\n\r\n5. **Implement the action plan:** The plan is put into action, and the individual is supported in taking the necessary steps.\r\n\r\n6. **Evaluate and assess the outcomes:** The mental health professional and the individual assess the effectiveness of the action plan and make adjustments if needed.","reference":"Dow lecture slides. Neuroscience module. Subject: Behavioural sciences Topic: Crisis Intervention, Sub-topic: Robert's seven-stage crisis intervention model.","responses":[{"text":"Develop and formulate an action plan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plan and conduct a crisis intervention","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Generate and explore alternatives","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Establish follow-up plan and agreement","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Deal with feelings and emotions","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

